Repo-ready spec

GIF Inline Rendering Protocol — GIRP v1.0

Goal

Enable pasted or uploaded animated GIFs to render as animated media inside chat rather than as a static first frame.

User story

As a user, when I paste or upload a GIF that animates in other apps, I want it to animate in chat so I can communicate with motion, timing, and punchline intact.

Functional requirements
	1.	Animated asset detection
	•	Detect whether uploaded or pasted media is:
	•	animated GIF
	•	animated WebP
	•	short loopable video masquerading as GIF source
	•	Do not classify animated media as static image based on first-frame preview alone.
	2.	Preserve original asset
	•	Store original uploaded binary separately from preview thumbnail.
	•	Preview generation must not replace the source asset for rendering.
	3.	Renderer routing
	•	If asset is animated:
	•	route to animated media renderer
	•	If asset is static:
	•	route to image renderer
	4.	Playback mode
	•	Preferred:
	•	autoplay once asset is visible
	•	loop while onscreen
	•	Fallback:
	•	tap-to-play if autoplay policy disallows motion
	5.	Graceful degradation
	•	If device settings prefer reduced motion:
	•	show still image with “Play GIF” overlay
	•	If asset too large:
	•	transcode to optimized loopable MP4/WebM preview
	•	preserve original asset for download/open
	6.	Clipboard-aware paste handling
	•	When pasting from apps that preserve animated payloads:
	•	inspect pasteboard UTI/MIME
	•	prefer animated payload over rasterized preview
	7.	Message composer preview
	•	Before send, show badge:
	•	GIF
	•	Animated
	•	So user knows whether animation survived ingestion

⸻

Non-functional requirements
	•	Max startup latency for visible playback: under 300 ms after message render
	•	Memory-safe playback for long chats
	•	Pause playback offscreen
	•	Respect low power mode and reduced motion settings
	•	No arbitrary remote script execution
	•	Sanitize metadata

